{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/nlp-with-naive-bayes-feature-selection-in-python-15c4d327aad5", "time": 1683006681.822815, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/nlp-with-naive-bayes-feature-selection-in-python-15c4d327aad5/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "Text classification with feature selection using Naive Bayes likelihoods | by Ben Johnson-Laird | Towards Data Science", "h1": "Text classification with feature selection using Naive Bayes likelihoods", "description": "In this post, I will discuss how it is possible to determine important features using Naive Bayes likelihoods, i.e. P(feature | class). The assumption is that we have a text classification task\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "https://github.com/benlaird/tweet_sentiment/blob/master/feature_selection.py", "anchor_text": "https://github.com/benlaird/tweet_sentiment/blob/master/feature_selection.py", "paragraph_index": 12}], "all_paragraphs": ["In this post, I will discuss how it is possible to determine important features using Naive Bayes likelihoods, i.e. P(feature | class).", "The assumption is that we have a text classification task where, as an initial step, we will tokenize and lemmatize the words into features. The question then becomes which features have the most predictive power in the classification task.", "For simplicity, we will consider this artificial toy weather data set where the features consist of nine weather-related English terms and the dependent variable indicates if the weather is \u201csuitable\u201d using some unspecified criteria.", "Since this is just an illustrative study, I won\u2019t bother splitting into training and testing sets. Running a Naive Bayes classification against the full feature set gives these results:", "Next, computing the feature likelihoods p(feature | class) gives this:", "Here I am sorting by the absolute difference of the likelihoods between the two classes. You can see that the feature windy is the most telling: occurring three times more often in unsuitable weather (0.27) than suitable weather (0.09). The calm and mild features are highly predictive, being only mentioned in suitable weather. While the feature overcast has no predictive power at all, being equally likely to occur in both suitable and unsuitable weather.", "Next, I will rerun the Naive Bayes classification with just the top three features: windy, calm & mild:", "You can see that the accuracy has improved by 11 percentage points.", "Also note, crucially, that since we have reduced the feature set from nine to three, the feature likelihoods used by the naive Bayes classifier have changed too:", "A comparison of the actuals vs predictions:", "In conclusion, one can see that feature selection based on the discriminating ability of conditional likelihood probabilities can improve precision & recall performance.", "Of course this, dataset is extremely simplistic and results may vary. In my next blog post, I will try to apply this approach with a much larger corpus of tweets.", "I will now highlight some features of the implementation. The full Python code is here: https://github.com/benlaird/tweet_sentiment/blob/master/feature_selection.py", "The callable function called by the built-in Python function SelectKBest:", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes.", "Data scientist & software engineer \u2014 with a background in machine learning, statistics & natural language processing"], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2F15c4d327aad5&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Open in app"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fnlp-with-naive-bayes-feature-selection-in-python-15c4d327aad5&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global